observations.recommendation:
We recommended that the Municipal Mayor direct the:
Municipal Accountant and the Liaison Officer for PHIC to exert additional effort to reconcile beginning balances of the inter-agency payable accounts – Due to GSIS, Due to Pag-IBIG, and Due to PhilHealth, related to prior years’ transactions and address identified discrepancies for the current year, implement the necessary adjustments and promptly remit any outstanding balances;
Municipal Budget Officer and HRMO-designate to ensure timely and complete submission of the annual schedule of plantilla personnel and copies of the CSC-confirmed appointments to the AAO, Municipal Accountant and the Liaison Officer for PHIC which will be used by the same to update information of the Municipal employees to the concerned agencies, such as new salary rates, employment status, position, and such other pertinent information;
Liaison Officer for PHIC to utilize the schedule of plantilla personnel and copies of the CSC-confirmed appointment in updating employee records in the EPRs and accordingly, reconcile the updated list with the Agency payroll and communicate the noted variance with the Accounting Office.; and
AAO, Liaison Officer for PHIC, and the Municipal Accountant to regularly reconcile their records to ensure that the monthly premiums and loan deductions from the payrolls/disbursement vouchers accurately match the amount to be remitted to GSIS, Pag-IBIG, and PhilHealth.

We reiterated the prior year recommendations that the Municipal Mayor direct the BAC to:
Ensure that the APP is prepared in accordance with the guidelines and prescribed downloadable forms available on the GPPB website, consistent with the pertinent provisions of RA No. 9184 and GPPB Circular No. 07-2015;
Consolidate all procurement activities including items in the APP-CSE and all PAPs, regardless of funding source;
Schedule each procurement activity with specificity, by clearly indicating the exact month, day, and year;
Adopt competitive bidding (public bidding) as the general mode of procurement and only resort to alternative modes if all the conditions set forth under Annex H of the 2016 revised IRR of RA 9184 are met; and
Ensure that all personnel involved in procurement are adequately trained and continuously updated on the latest developments in procurement laws, including the proper preparation of the APP, and that they effectively apply this knowledge in the discharge of their duties.

In addition, we recommended that the Municipal Mayor direct all end-user units to submit their respective PPMPs in a timely manner, ensuring that these are complete, properly accomplished, and include a detailed schedule for each procurement activity.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor, being the head of the Procuring Entity to:

Require the end-user or implementing units of the Procuring Entity to formulate their respective PPMPs for their different PPAs;



Direct the BAC and BAC Secretariat to appropriately fill out the specifics of individual projects in the Bid Data Sheet, Special Conditions of the Contract, Specifications, and Bill of Quantities to ensure that the bidders capture the necessary information to prepare their bids accurately;

Require the BAC and BAC Secretariat to use the updated forms so that the mandatory provisions were included; and,



Direct the BAC and the BAC Secretariat to familiarize themselves with the provisions of the IRR of RA 9184 and their functions and responsibilities in the conduct of procurement to ensure the integrity of the process.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor to instruct the: 
a. BAC to prepare the procurement documents and POs to ensure that adequate information is supplied; 



b. GSO-Designate and Municipal Accountant to formulate inspection guidelines or procedures Municipal Treasurer to act as the GSO es which should be incorporated in their Citizen’s Charter to ensure that the goods received conform with the specifications in the procurement documents.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor:
 
Instruct the Municipal Accountant to prepare all accounting records required under the Manual on the NGAS for LGUs to ensure proper trail of all financial transactions and occurrences; 

Assess and explore the possibility of adding additional staff/filling up vacancies in the Municipal Accounting Office who have competencies and skills in Finance, Accounting, and Record Keeping;

Direct the Municipal Budget Officer to prepare the SAAOB which is rightfully under her responsibility; and



Direct Human Resource Designate to prepare the payroll and compile the DTRs.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive direct:

The Municipal Engineer to provide the Municipal Accountant and the Municipal General Service Officer/Municipal Treasurer with the complete description and cost segregation of road components for road projects;



The Municipal Accountant to:

Keep and maintain subsidiary records for roads and road components for every road network;



Prepare a lapsing schedule for the computation of the depreciation for each component at the end of each year;



The Inventory Committee to:

Conduct an inventory of the local roads under the jurisdiction of the Municipality;



Render a Report on the physical count of the Road Network System.



The Municipal General Service Officer/Municipal Treasurer to:

Render a Report on Local Road Network and Road Map; and



Keep a complete Local Road Network Property Card for all roads and its components.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive direct the Bids and Awards Committee to:

Ensure that the APP is completely filled up following the step-by-step guide found in the GPPB website under downloadable forms which is in accordance with the pertinent provisions of RA No. 9184 and GPPB Circular No. 07-2015.

Assign specific and realistic time frames and schedules for each procurement activity by indicating the month, day, and year;

We have recommended the Municipal Mayor to:

instruct the Municipal Accountant to exert more effort for him to be able to conduct verification, analysis, and validation of the existence of the non-moving accounts. Thereafter, recognize provision for Allowance for Impairment for the applicable accounts determined to have a no and/or low collection rate and include adequate disclosure pertaining to the provision on the Notes to Financial Statements; 

